    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-02-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-02-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="43"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d43">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Dayton</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 473.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-02-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">February</hi> 8, 1864.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your despatch of the 22d ultimo, No. 404, has
                    been received.</p>
                <p>You will have learned from instructions which are on their way to you that the
                    President was not satisfied with the course which the French government had
                    thought proper to pursue with reference to the Florida, Georgia, and
                    Rappahannock. It appears, however, from your note to Mr. Drouyn de l’Huys of <pb
                        facs="0055" n="35" xml:id="pg_35"/> the 22d ultimo, that you had
                    anticipated, in respect to the Florida at least, the instructions adverted to.
                    Our own law, as you are aware, forbids not only the fitting out and arming in
                    our ports of vessels to make war on a country with which we may be at peace, but
                    also prohibits any augmentation of the armament of a foreign belligerent in a
                    United States port. We have a right to expect the same prohibition in French
                    ports against insurgent vessels. There must necessarily be some anxiety here
                    upon this subject until the determination of the French government can be
                    known.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William L. Dayton</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.,
                            &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
